00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
In this lesson, we will cover one of the most fundamental

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
grammar concepts on the SAT: the complete sentence.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Understanding what makes a sentence complete is the key
to every punctuation question in the Boundaries category.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
A complete sentence must have three things.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.500
First, a subject — the noun or pronoun that performs
or receives the action.

00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:33.000
Second, a finite verb — a verb that shows tense,
such as runs, ran, or has run.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:40.000
And third, a complete thought — the sentence must not
leave the reader expecting more information.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:57.000
When a complete sentence can stand on its own —
when it does not depend on another clause to make sense —

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.000
we call it an independent clause.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Look at this example: "The engineers tested the new prototype."

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
The word "engineers" is the subject.
"Tested" is the finite verb.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
And the thought is complete.
This is an independent clause.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Here is a reliable test you can use on the SAT.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Cover the clause you are evaluating. Read it on its own.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.000
If it can stand alone as a complete sentence,
it is an independent clause.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:50.000
If it cannot — if it sounds unfinished or begins with a word like
"although," "because," or "since" —

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.000
it is a dependent clause or a fragment.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Compare these two examples.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
The first begins with the word "although."
Because of that word, the clause is dependent.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
It sounds unfinished — we are waiting for the other half
of the sentence. This is a fragment.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:20.000
The second example removes "although,"
and now the clause stands alone perfectly.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
It is a complete sentence.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
When two independent clauses appear together, the SAT expects
you to punctuate them correctly.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.000
You have three valid options: a period, a semicolon,
or a comma followed by a coordinating conjunction —

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
for, and, nor, but, or, yet, or so.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Here, a period or a semicolon correctly separates
these two complete sentences.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
The most common mistake students make is the comma splice.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:13.000
This happens when a comma alone connects two independent clauses.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
A comma by itself is not strong enough to join
two complete sentences.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:27.000
If you see a comma separating two full sentences on the SAT,
that answer choice is wrong.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Here is your takeaway.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Before you choose any punctuation answer on the SAT,
identify both clauses.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Test each one: can it stand alone as a complete sentence?

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Once you know which clauses are independent,
the correct punctuation follows the rule.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Every Boundaries decision starts with identifying complete sentences.
